%U A394364 4,3,1,3,32,16,36,18,18,12,1,12,15,12,15,12,39,19,4,19,8
%N A394364 The final square visited by a knight moving on a square-spiral numbered board, starting from square n, and always moving to the lowest available unvisited square while never crossing the path of any previous step (Cf. A394363), or -1 if no such square exists.
%C A394364 There are three starting squares, n = 8, 43, 112, that lead to the path being infinite - this is due to the path of earlier steps forming a repetitive and near circular wall around the central squares that subsequent steps cannot cross. See the attached image for n = 8.
%C A394364 There are only 36 possible squares that all finite walks can end on, these being 1, 3, 4, 8, 9, ..., 111, 114, 280, 422. The first path to end on square 1 is that starting on square 3, whose entire path is 3, 6, 9, 12, 1, after which the path ends. The first path to end on square 422, the largest value, is that starting on square 698, which ends after visited 87 squares. See the attached image.
%C A394364 See A394363 for more information, and A394365 for the total number of visited squares when starting from n.
%H A394364 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394364/b394364.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A394364 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394364/a394364_1.png">Image of the path for a(8) = -1</a>. This is the first of three infinite walks. The first 5000 visited squares are shown.
%H A394364 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394364/a394364.png">Image of the path for a(698) = 422</a>. This is the largest possible finite end square. The start and end squares are colored green and red respectively, while the 8 squares around the final square that the knight is blocked from stepping to are colored blue.
%e A394364 a(1) = 53. See A394363.
%e A394364 a(8) = -1. See the attached image.
%e A394364 a(698) = 422. See the attached image.
%Y A394364 Cf. A394363, A394365 (path lengths), A316667, A336208, A383185.
